which is an album that to be completely
honest while i know that a lot of people
are living
and dying by this lp it's a seminal

i do like a lot of the musical
characteristics of the dismemberment
plans tracks i like they're typically
jagged and very tight drum beats that
are at times
dance music influence the very grooving

i don't want to say aggressive since it

personally
interested because this really seems to

new album of theirs to me feels like
nearly everything i remember about the
dismemberment plan
minus and this is a big minus
minus
all the eccentricities even the drumming
has mellowed out in a pretty big way
with maybe the most energetic and
danceable track on this album being
mexico city christmas for the most part
the drum beats do not feel as sharp or
as jagged and they're thrown in the back
of the mix a little bit the guitars have
a much more equal balance with the
synthesizers now and they come off much
more gentle as well i think the most
unchanged characteristic about this
whole record is maybe travis morrison's
voice again you don't have him reaching
up into those really frantic highs of
his range but he does still have this
vocal that feels really youthful feels
really boyish and yet there's this
strange vibrato to it and this really
earnest tone all that's really occurring
on this record is dismemberment plan is
is merely working with their softer
gentler more playful side there are
moments when the music in my opinion
shoots for a blatantly feel good mood
kind of like the track daddy was a real
good dancer even though there is sort of
a sad personal story going on in the
lyrics there i'm definitely trying to
advocate for the direction that the band
is moving in from an outside perspective
i don't think this is a terrible record
but does it appeal to me not really the
truth is a lot of the music a lot of the
guitar phrasing and a lot of the
lyricism on this album are
insultingly simplistic like
the track let's go to the dogs tonight
with the opening lyrics about
well what is it i'll be the sugar and
you'll be the cream i'll be the dreamer
and you be the dream and of course these
lyrics are delivered with a flow that
kind of feels like it's it's paced out
like a children's rhyme or something and
i mean that could have totally been
intentional maybe that is intentional
especially with the the level of rhyming
and imagery going on here too but
i definitely don't feel like travis
morrison
juxtaposed this in a way where it
actually feels like an adult can enjoy
it not only that but there are tracks on
here like go and get it where the music
feels much more
well suited for a band like ok go that's
how saccharin the dismemberment plan
sounds on this record and while that
wouldn't necessarily be a bad thing i
feel like the pop appeal of this record
isn't quite as high or as energetic or
as thrilling there are spots here that i
enjoy like the earnestness in the lyrics
on the track white collar white trash or
even how tender and and wonderfully
melodic the song looking is but as i've
said before
when it comes to more toned down tracks
more ballad driven tracks from the
dismemberment plan they just don't
really
thrill me they just don't really move me
i guess i could say so not only are
there moments where i just wish this
record was
a bit gutsier but for music that has a

it's not incredibly moving or in my
